the competing visions of Westminster’s identity which their presence engendered.Different chapters study the impact of the Reformation and of the building of Whitehall Palace; the problem of poverty and the politics of communal responsibility; the character and significance of the increasing gentry presence in the town; the nature and ideology of local governing elites; the struggles over the emerging townscape; and the changing religious culture of the area, including the problematic role of the post-Reformation Abbey.A comprehensive study of one of the most populous and influential towns in early modern England, this book covers the entire period from the Reformation to the Civil War. It will make fascinating reading for historians of English society, literature and religion in this period, as well as enthusiasts of London’s rich history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aPolitics and culturezGreat BritainxHistoryy16th century. 0aPolitics and culturezGreat BritainxHistoryy17th century. 0aPolitics and culture-Great Britain-History-16th century. 0aPolitics and culture-Great Britain-History-17th century. 0aReligion and politicszGreat BritainxHistoryy16th century. 0aReligion and politicszGreat BritainxHistoryy17th century. 0aReligion and politics-Great Britain-History-16th century. 0aReligion and politics-Great Britain-History-17th century. 0aWestminster (London, England)-History-16th century. 0aWestminster (London, England)-History-17th century. 0aWestminster (London, England)-Social life and customs-16th century. 0aWestminster (London, England)-Social life and customs-17th century. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / General.2bisacsh  aAbbey.  aCourt.  aHenry VIII's reign.  aSt Margaret's parish.  aSt Martin's parish.  aadministrative structure.  aaristocracy.  acorpor